\subsection{Unification}

Rules \rulename{uvar}-\rulename{ucon}-\rulename{utup} do conventional unification, decomposing
tuples where necessary.  Notice that |e_1 == e_2| reduces to its unified value.  For example,
|(3==3) + 7| reduces to |10|.

In rule \rulename{ucon} there are two uses of ``$=$'', but they are different!  The ``|k_1 == k_2|''
on the LHS is part of the syntax of Verse. In contrast
the ``$k_1 = k_2$'' in the side-condition is ``real'' equality: it means that |k_1| and |k_2| are the
same constant.

Rules \rulename{bind}, \rulename{promote}, and \rulename{swap} come into play when variables are involved.
First, \rulename{bind} says that when |x| is in scope, \emph{and does not already have a value in the heap} (hence |H^[x]| not |H^[x := v]|),
we may unify |x| with a value |v|, and replace the unbound |x| in the heap with the bound |x := v|, thus |H^[x:=v]|.
The side conditions ensure
\begin{itemize}
    \item $\freevars{v} \disjoint \boundvars{X}$ ensures that |v| does not mention a variable
      bound by the context |X|; if the rule fired, the right hand side would be ill-scoped.
    \item $\freevars{v} \disjoint \{x\}$ ensures that |v| does not mention |x| itself -- the ``occurs check''.
    \item $\freevars{v} \disjoint \valvars{|H^[x]|}$ ensures that we have fully applied rule \rulename{subst};
      without this there might be a hidden occurs-check error.  For example in this case:
      $$ |def (x, y:=x) in (x=y)| $$
      we must not fire rule \rulename{bind}.
\end{itemize}
Together, the latter two side conditions ensure that we never
get cycles in the heap.

Crucially, note that $X$ does not look inside |if|, |for|, or choice (|choice|).
For example
$$ |def x in (if(x==3) then e_1 else e_2)| $$
does
not unify |x| via \rulename{bind}; only variables bound by the \emph{innermost enclosing \hexp{}} can be unified.
Nor does $X$ look inside choices.  For example,
|def x in (x==2 choice x==3)| does not unify |x| via \rulename{bind}.

Rules \rulename{swap} and \rulename{promote} are there to allow \rulename{bind} to fire more often.
First, rule \rulename{swap} swaps |(hnf=x)| to |(x=hnf)|, which directly fits rule \rulename{bind}.
We just need to be careful that we cannot swap |(x=y)| to |(y=x)| and back forever; hence
using |hnf| rather than |v| in this rule.

\rulename{promote} is subtle, and deals with a case like
    $$ |def x in dots(def z in dots(x==(3,z))dots)dots| $$
We can't use \rulename{bind} directly, because it would be ill-scoped to add |x:=(3,z)|
to the outermost |def|. Instead we invent a fresh variable |y| (bound as a sibling to |x|),
substitute it for |z| in |v|, and unify it with |z|, thus
    $$ |def x,y in dots(def z in dots(x==(3,y); z=y)dots)dots| $$
Now  \rulename{bind} can bind bind |x| to |(3,y)|:
    $$ |def x:=(3,y),y in dots(def z in dots(z=y)dots)dots| $$
and all is well.

\subsection{Choice and failure}

Rule \rulename{choose} is the crucial one: it duplicates the entire |def| context.  But note the
\emph{choice-free} context |CX|!  For example, the expression
$$
|def (x,y) in (x == (3 choice 4)) ; (y == (9 choice 2)); (x,y)|
$$
should yield the values |(3,9)|, |(3,2)|, |(4,9)|, |(4,2)|, in that order.
To get the order right, we must apply \rulename{choose} to the first choice |(3 choice 4)| first, and only
then to the second |(9 choice 2)|.  This is achieved by using |CX| in \rulename{choose} to ensure that only the
\emph{leftmost} choice can be chosen.

%\joachim{I did not initially manage to understand why |apply v; hole| is not a choice context, i.e. why we need |cop| and |op|. I also tried to combine the two in Redex, in case a failing test would enlighten me, but none did. Can someone add an example? Ah, maybe the crucial property of a choice-free expression is that it is guaranteed to \emph{evaluate} to at most a single value (It still allows to evaluate to |fail|). Ok, makes sense now. I'll leave this note here and add an example later.}

Rule \rulename{fail} collapes an expression with a nexted |fail| into a single |fail|.  It uses the |X| evaluation
context, which looks more deeply into an expression than does |CX|.  For example
$$
|def (x,y) in (x == (3 choice 4)) ; (y == (9 choice 2)); fail; (x,y)|
$$
can fail immediately; we don't need to perform the choices for |x| and |y| first, because they will all fail.
The use of |X| also means that a |def h in (2, fail plus 3, 7)| will collapse to |fail| by \rulename{fail};
we do not need rules like $|fail plus e| \movesto |fail|$.

But note that $X$ does not look inside choices.  For example, |def h in (fail choice e)| does not collapse
to |fail| by \rulename{fail}.

\subsection{Functions and application}

Rule \rulename{app-lam} is a rather simple and beautiful $\beta$-reduction rule.
Notice that |apply| is one of the primitive functions in $cop$.

A tuples/array behaves like a (finite) function, and can be applied to a numeric value
in \rulename{app-arr} to index it.

A recursive definition gets unrolled one step when it is used in the function position of |apply| by rule \rulename{app-rec}.
If the body of the recursive definition is a function then reduction will eventually proceed.

\subsection{Conditionals}

In Verse, an |if|-expression does not evaluate its condition to a Boolean true or false.  Instead
it tests whether its condition succeeds (i.e. returns one or more values) or fails (returning no values).
For example |if (x=3) then e_1 else e_2| tries to unify |x| and |3|; if that succeds (returning one value, namely |3|)
the |if| returns |e_1|, otherwise it returns |e_2|.

Comparision operators succeed or fail, rather than returning a Boolean
(as in most languages). For example |(x>3)| suceeds if |x| is greater
than 3, returning |x|; and fails if not.

It is very important that in a conditional |(if (x=3) then ...)| we
treat |x| as ``rigid'': the conditional is intended to \emph{test}
|x|'s value, rather \emph{giving} |x| its value!  That is why rule \rulename{b-val}
does not look inside the condition of an |if| (look at the syntax of context |X| used in that rule).

\subsection{The Equality Principle}

Verse cleaves to the following principle.

\begin{quote}
\textbf{The Equality Principle (EP)}.
For any choice-free, side-effect-free expression |e|, and values |v_1| and |v_2|,
if |(e = v_1)| is inhabited, and |(e = v_2)| is inhabited, then |v_1|=|v_2|.
\end{quote}
For example suppose |misBehaves = t => def{x} in x|, so that (if we are not careful) the call |misBehaves()| returns
a fresh, unbound logical variable.  Now |(misBehaves() = 3)| and |(misBehaves() = 4)| will both succeed (be inhabited),
but 3 is not equal to 4.  So this wouldn't satisfy the EP.

Another way of putting this is that |=| behaves as an equivalence relation in Verse.

\subsection{Source Verse}

In the Verse source language we do not write explicit |def|s. Instead, they are added
by a simple preprocessing step, that introduces a variable |x| in the innermost
|def| that encloses all its uses.
\simon{It's hard to say more until we say more about Source Verse.}

In the arms of a choice |(e_1 choice e_2)| we add a |def h in e_1| around |e_1| if
|e_1| introduces any new variables; and similarly |e_2|.
\simon{This was a nice little simplification.}

\subsection{Examples}

\begin{example}
  $$\begin{array}{rcl}
    \multicolumn{3}{l}{|def (x,y) in x==3; y==add^(x,1)|} \\
    \rulename{bind}  & \movesto & |def (x:=3,y) in 3; y==add^(x,1)| \\
    \rulename{seq}   & \movesto & |def (x:=3,y) in y==add^(x,1)| \\
    \rulename{subst} & \movesto & |def (x:=3,y) in y==add^(3,1)| \\
    \rulename{p-add} & \movesto & |def (x:=3,y) in y==4| \\
    \rulename{bind}  & \movesto & |def (x:=3,y:=4) in 4| \\
    \end{array}$$
\end{example}

\begin{example}
  $$\begin{array}{rcl}
    \multicolumn{3}{l}{|def (x,y) in y==add^(x,1); x==3; y|} \\
    \rulename{bind}  & \movesto & |def (x:=3,y) in y==add^(x,1); 3; y| \\
    \rulename{subst} & \movesto & |def (x:=3,y) in y==add^(3,1); 3; y| \\
    \rulename{p-add} & \movesto & |def (x:=3,y) in y==4; 3; y| \\
    \rulename{bind} & \movesto & |def (x:=3,y:=4) in 4; 3; y| \\
    \rulename{p-seq}(twice) & \movesto & |def (x:=3,y:=4) in y| \\
    \rulename{subst} & \movesto & |def (x:=3,y:=4) in 4|
    \end{array}$$
  The evaluation of |add^(x,1)| is stuck, and hence so is the unification
  |(y==add^(x,1))|.  But the evaluation context |X| allows us to apply rule \rulename{bind}
  in the \emph{second} argument of sequencing, which gives a value to |x| in the heap.
  That allows the |add| to proceed.  So ``later'' instructions can unblock ``earlier'' ones.
\end{example}

\begin{example}
  $$\begin{array}{rcl}
    \multicolumn{3}{l}{|def (x,y) in y==add^(x,1); ((x==3) choice (x==77))|} \\
    \rulename{choose} & \movesto & |(def (x,y) in y==add^(x,1); x==3) choice| \\
    & & |(def (x,y) in y==add^(x,1); x==77)| \\
    \rulename{bind} (twice) & \movesto & |(def (x:=3,y) in y==add^(x,1); 3) choice| \\
    & & |(def (x:=77,y) in y==add^(x,1); 77)| \\
    \rulename{subst} (twice) & \movesto & |(def (x:=3,y) in y==add^(3,1); 3) choice| \\
    & & |(def (x:=77,y) in y==add^(77,1); 77)| \\
    \rulename{p-add} (twice) & \movesto & |(def (x:=3,y) in y==4; 3) choice (def (x:=77,y) in y==78; 77)| \\
    \rulename{bind}(twice) & \movesto & |(def (x:=3,y:=4) in 4; 3) choice (def (x:=77,y:=78) in 78; 77)| \\
    \rulename{seq}(twice) & \movesto & |(def (x:=3,y:=4) in 3) choice (def (x:=77,y:=78) in 77)| \\
    \end{array}$$
  As before, the unification |y==add^(x,1)| is stuck until we get a value for |x|.
  But this time we get two different values for |x| in the two branches of the choice.
  The crucial rule \rulename{choose} duplicates the heap and the expression that surround
  the choice, allowing execution to proceed entirely independently in the two copies.
\end{example}

\begin{example} $$
  \begin{array}{rcl}
    \multicolumn{3}{l}{|apply^(x => add^(x, 1), 2)|} \\
    \rulename{app-lam} & \movesto & |def t in t == 2; add^(t, 1)| \\
